  "text": "For action recognition, a unique set of action features are used as stated previously. In what follows, we thus focus on the description of our pose-indexed depth features, which are used in the first two types of regressors, R (c) j , and R m . Our feature representation can be regarded as an extension of the popular depth features as discussed in [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] by incorporating the idea of pose-indexed features [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] to model 3D objects. We start by focusing on a joint j with its current 3D location x ∈ R 3 , where a 3D offset u can be obtained by random sampling from the home pose. Let gΘ 1:j (u) denote the Lie group left action of current object poseΘ 1:j applied onto u. Now the 3D location of the offset is naturally x + gΘ 1:j (u), and its projection onto 2D image plane under current camera view is denoted asū = Proj x + gΘ 1:j (u) . Similarly we can obtain another random offsetv. For a 2D pixel locationx = Proj x ∈ R 2 of an image patch I containing the object of interest, its depth value can be denoted as d I (x). Now we are ready to construct a feature φ I,(ū,v) (x) or its short-hand notation φ, by considering two 2D offsets positionsū,v fromx:",
